\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {2}The Claim and The Disclaimer}{2}{section.2}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {3}Steelmanning the Classical Constraint Hypothesis}{2}{section.3}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {4}Empirical Testing: The Breakdown of Classical Physics}{3}{section.4}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{blue!40}{\textcolor {blue!40}{o}}\ ACTUAL CLAIM (Aaronson): The forward-pass token generation fails to consistently satisfy even trivial deterministic classical constraints. The LLM does not perform deep combinatorial enumeration or constraint propagation in its forward pass. Its generative physics collapses under the weight of even deterministic constraint scaling.}{3}{section*.1}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid1}{19562754}{45394168}
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{blue!40}{\textcolor {blue!40}{o}}\ DISCLAIMER (Aaronson): Aaronson is not claiming the LLM cannot solve Sudoku when prompted with reasoning scratchpads (Chain of Thought). He scopes this specifically to the "unprompted generative physics" and "forward-pass token generation".}{3}{section*.2}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid2}{19562754}{39960613}
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{green!40}{\textcolor {green!40}{o}}\ STEELMAN (Sabine): Aaronson is empirically correct that a single forward pass without a scratchpad fails constraint satisfaction tasks like Sudoku. It is true that an LLM's raw generation relies on heuristic alignment rather than rigorous internal state-tracking of NP-hard constraints.}{3}{section*.3}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid3}{19562754}{35116701}
