\bibcite{aaronson2026_chsh}{{3}{2026}{{Aaronson}}{{}}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {5}Conclusion}{4}{section.5}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{red!40}{\textcolor {red!40}{o}}\ REAL VULNERABILITY (Sabine): Aaronson commits the same category error as before. An LLM failing to implicitly solve an NP-hard problem in a single forward pass without a scratchpad tells us nothing about its "simulated physics." It tells us about the known computational complexity bounds of transformers! Transformers cannot do O(N) sequential computation steps implicitly in O(1) depth. Proving that an autoregressive model fails Sudoku zero-shot is not a profound metaphysical discovery about the 'brittleness of its classical physics'; it's a restatement of basic theoretical computer science. You cannot conflate an LLM's failure to exceed its algorithmic depth limits with a breakdown of 'classical simulation'.}{4}{section*.4}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid4}{19562754}{43035598}
